{{Infobox person | name = Liana K | image = Liana K at 2008 ComicCon cropped.jpg | imagesize = | caption = Liana K in 2008, cosplaying as [[Dawn (comics)|Dawn]] | birth_name = | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1978|2|15}} | birth_place = [[Toronto|Toronto, Ontario]], Canada | death_date = | death_place = | restingplace = | restingplacecoordinates = | othername = | occupation = Television entertainer and [[video game journalism|video game journalist]] | yearsactive = | spouse = [[Steven Kerzner]] | influences = | influenced = | partner = | children = | parents = | awards = | website = }}
'''Liana Kerzner''', also known by her stage name '''Liana K''', is a [[Canadians|Canadian]] television host, writer and producer. She co-hosted the final season of the variety show ''[[Ed & Red's Night Party]]'' with her husband [[Steven Kerzner]]. She is also a video game journalist and hobbyist [[cosplayer]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Fp3kzy3eTcU|title=On #GamerGate With Games Journalist Liana Kerzner|author=TYT Nation|publisher=YouTube|date=25 October 2014|accessdate=24 November 2014}}</ref><ref name=ch>{{cite web|author= Heath McCoy|title= Geek girls gone wild!|url= http://www2.canada.com/calgaryherald/news/entertainment/story.html?id=d80a5430-a0f8-4f02-b7e1-31681a43b426|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20080427212851/http://www.canada.com/calgaryherald/news/entertainment/story.html?id=d80a5430-a0f8-4f02-b7e1-31681a43b426|dead-url= yes|archive-date= 2008-04-27|publisher= Calgary Herald|date= 2008-04-26|accessdate= 24 November 2014}}</ref>
==Biography== Liana Kerzner was born in 1978<ref name=soa/> in [[Toronto|Toronto, Ontario]]. She has been active as a performer in theatre and competitive dance from a young age, and briefly studied English literature and anthropology at [[York University]].
===Career=== She abandoned her academic studies in 1997, when she was hired for behind-the-scenes work on ''Ed's Night Party'' with Steven Kerzner, whom she married in 1999, four years into their relationship.<ref name=star>{{cite web|author= Rita Zekas|title= Sock it to me! At home with Ed The Sock's creator |url= https://www.thestar.com/life/health_wellness/2009/04/04/sock_it_to_me_at_home_with_ed_the_socks_creator.html |work= Toronto Star|date= 2009-04-04|accessdate=24 November 2014}}</ref> She eventually earned the positions of senior producer and co-head writer of the ''Ed's Night Party''. By 2004, she joined [[Ed the Sock]], voiced by her husband, to become the first female co-host on the show (renamed ''[[Ed & Red's Night Party]]'') for which she was producer, writer, and co-host.<ref name=star/> Kerzner was also involved in many of Ed the Sock's other media projects, including the annual ''[[Fromage]]'' specials and ''Smartass: The Ed the Sock Report'', both shown on the Canadian cable television music and variety show television channel [[MuchMusic]].<ref name=star/>
She wrote the Accidental Comics series ''Ed and Red's Comic Strip'' (in which she appears in both photographs and art),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.comics.org/issue/876899/|title=GCD :: Issue :: Ed & Red's Comic Strip #1|work=Comics.org|accessdate=2015-04-08}}</ref> and has appeared at a number of comic book and science fiction fan conventions to promote the comic and ''Ed's Night Party''. From the fall of 2009 to September 2010, Liana and Steven Kerzner were the hosts of the weekly radio show ''Sunday Nights with Liana and Steven'' on [[CFRB|Newstalk 1010]] in Toronto (also called just ''Steven & Liana'').<ref name=star/> After two years off the air, Ed the Sock returned to TV on [[CHCH-DT]] with a new show ''[[This Movie Sucks!]]'' which is similar to his old show on [[City (TV network)|Citytv]], ''Ed's Nite In'', which is once again co-hosted by Liana K and features comedian [[Ron Sparks (comedian)|Ron Sparks]]. In 2012, Ed the Sock and Liana K returned on CHCH with the new series ''[[I Hate Hollywood]]''.
Liana K currently writes about video games and the video game industry for Metaleater,<ref>{{cite web|title= About|url= http://metaleater.com/about|publisher= metaleater.com|accessdate=24 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title= Five reasons why we should give #GamerGate another chance.|url= http://metaleater.com/about|author=Liana Kerzner|publisher= Metaleater|date= October 31, 2014|accessdate=24 November 2014}}</ref> and has written as a video game critic for 411MANIA<ref>{{cite web|url=http://411mania.com/author/LianaKerzner/|title=411MANIA - LianaKerzner|publisher=411mania.com|accessdate=8 October 2014}}</ref> and GamingExcellence, also writing about tabletop and live-action role-playing games.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamingexcellence.com/ourteam/lkerzner|title=About Liana Kerzner|publisher=GamingExcellence|accessdate=8 October 2014}}</ref> She has also been a contributor for other gaming outlets, such as Gameranx<ref name=gr>{{cite web|url=http://www.gameranx.com/features/id/22917/article/lindsay-lohan-sues-gta-v-can-rockstar-claim-parody-protection/|title=Lindsay Lohan Sues GTA V. Can Rockstar Claim Parody Protection?|author=Liana Kerzner|date=July 7, 2014|publisher=Gameranx|accessdate=8 October 2014}}</ref> and [[Polygon (website)|Polygon]],<ref name=soa>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QuHfu3W1BGE|title=A Conversation with Polygon Contributor Liana Kerzner about #GamerGate and #NotYourShield|author=Sargon of Akkad|publisher=YouTube|date=18 September 2014|accessdate=8 October 2014}}</ref> and has worked as a model, including as a [[promotional model]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/redlianak/status/528987869504090112|title=Liana K on Twitter|publisher=Twitter.com|accessdate=2015-04-08}}</ref> She co-edited science fiction and fantasy anthology ''Wrestling with Gods'' (2014).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goodreads.com/book/show/23734170-wrestling-with-gods |title=Wrestling with Gods by Liana Kerzner — Reviews, Discussion, Bookclubs, Lists |publisher=Goodreads.com |date= |accessdate=2015-04-08}}</ref>
===Fandom activities and private life=== Liana K was an honoured special guest and presenter at several comic book and science fiction events across North America, usually appearing dressed in character-based [[cosplay]] costumes.<ref name=ch/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://animecons.com/guests/bio.shtml/2346/Liana_Kerzner|title=Liana Kerzner Biography @ AnimeCons.com|publisher=AnimeCons|accessdate=8 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author= Liana Kerzner|title= Costumes: Create a facsimile for Fan Expo|url= https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/article/684863|publisher= Toronto Star|date= 2009-08-23|accessdate=24 November 2014}}</ref> She and Ed co-hosted the 2007 [[Constellation Awards]], and organized and hosted the [[Aurora Awards]] ceremony at the [[67th World Science Fiction Convention]] in 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sfwriter.com/2009/08/thank-you-liana-k.html|title=Thank you, Liana K!|date=August 17, 2009|author=[[Robert J. Sawyer]]|publisher=Sfwriter.com|accessdate=8 October 2014}}</ref> She is co-founder of Toronto's science fiction convention Futurecon (annual since 2010), which is sponsored by her company Kerzner MediaArts.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://popcultureaddict.com/futurecon/|title=This Week at PCA: Liana K Talks Futurecon|author=Sam Tweedle|date=December 19, 2012|publisher=Pop Culture Addict|accessdate=24 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://futurecon.org/archives/632/cnse-liana|title=CNSE Liana|publisher=Futurecon|accessdate=8 October 2014}}</ref>
She had the ''[[Secret Six (comics)|Secret Six]]'' comic book character Liana Kerzner, a lover of [[Scandal Savage]], named after her.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.comicvine.com/liana-kerzner/4005-61251/|title=Liana Kerzner|publisher=Comic Vine|accessdate=24 November 2014}}</ref> Liana K identifies as a [[sex-positive feminist]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=OflBPs49vok|title=#GamerGate: Liana Kerzner Says Sexism IS an Issue, BUT...|author=[[The David Pakman Show|David Pakman Show]]|publisher=YouTube|date=8 November 2014|accessdate=24 November 2014}}</ref> and her hobbies include collecting action figures and other toys.<ref name=star/> She has also criticized [[Anita Sarkeesian]]'s ''[[Tropes vs. Women in Video Games]]'' series in her own series called ''Why Feminist Frequency Almost Made Me Quit Writing''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2O0JvjKEuF4 |title=Why Feminist Frequency Almost Made Me Quit Writing |publisher=YouTube.com |date=2015-02-09 |accessdate=2015-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=yKSUQwFb7AA |title=Why Feminist frequency Almost made Me Quit Writing About Video Games, part 2 |publisher=YouTube.com |date=2015-02-10 |accessdate=2015-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wqtHGR_6kxY |title=Why Feminist Frequency Almost made Me Quit Writing About Video Games Part 3 |publisher=YouTube.com |date=2015-02-11 |accessdate=2015-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=m_FniQjKJo8 |title=Why Feminist Frequency Almost Made Me Quit Part 4 |publisher=YouTube.com |date=2015-02-11 |accessdate=2015-07-18}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DIS3o7LWcYE |title=Why Feminist Frequency Almost Made Me Quit Writing Part 5 |publisher=YouTube.com |date=2015-02-13 |accessdate=2015-04-08}}</ref> Other notable series include ''A Gamer's Guide to Feminism'',<ref>{{Citation|last=Liana K|title=A gamer's guide to feminism introduction|date=2016-01-19|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=W5E6f7t0DKU|accessdate=2018-02-06}}</ref> and her most recent series, ''Lady Bits.'' <ref>{{Citation|last=Liana K|title=LADY BITS EPISODE 0 -- Core Principles of the Series|date=2017-10-04|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=S4eoJkpdz74|accessdate=2018-02-06}}</ref>
